results.title: Original Rare 1920 Stephenson Prohibition Whiskey Prescription Doctor Willis Jones Antique Medical Bar Sedalia MO Missouri Pharmacy History
results.description:
A rare first year, first issue 1920 Prohibition Prescription for Whiskey...Oi (pint)...Sig: 1/2 oz every 4 hrs! This prescription was the FIRST of five, issued by the Treasury Department during the Prohibition. The doc had beautiful penmanship and "1920" prescriptions for "whiskey" are quite rare! Also, the majority of scripts were for frumenti, so the whiskey scripts are not as prevalent.

It is the ONLY prescription in which, "His street and No." was printed below the address line, while just as many women were having liquor prescriptions filled. Please see photos!

From the days of Al Capone, speakeasies and moonshine, this was the only legal way to drink liquor in the US!

The whiskey was prescribed for H. E. Stephenson, by Dr. Willis G. Jones, on November 16, 1920, and was stamped (filling date...oops) November 15, 1920, by Yunker-Lierman Drug Store in Sedalia, MO. It was issued by the Treasury Department and measures 6" x 3.5".

The prescription has some bends, light edge wear and age toning (not white/looks like it's from 1920), otherwise, condition is excellent...a great, historic 1920 Prohibition script...a personal all-time favorite!

This is a FANTASTIC piece of history and would be great to display in a pharmacy, speakeasy, distillery, doctor's office, museum, bar or office! I am happy to answer any questions, please feel free to email and thank you for your interest!

Pleased to combine shipping with other Prohibition Prescriptions, Liquor Licenses, Opium Forms & Pharmacy Labels. As always, many thanks to my regular customers for your continued patronage! :)

All items ship within 24 hours and I will contact you when I receive notification of any purchase, thank you! :)

Shop.policy_additional:
RING SIZE

I guarantee that your order will be made to the exact size and width you specify. If I make an error and send you the wrong size, I will create a new ring in the correct size specified in your original order and pay any postage both ways. 

It is very important to order the correct size, our rings are all made to order and even though I might be able to increase the ring by 1/4 size this is not guaranteed.

I recommend checking your size at a jewelry store, a couple if possible. Since narrow and wide rings will fit differently have your finger sized with a ring the width you plan to order. You may want to be sized more than once to ensure accuracy. Most jewelers use the bottom or leading edge of the ring to determine the size, some use the middle of the ring. We measure where the metal meets the mandrel on the leading edge. The frustrating part is that there are also slight variances between ring mandrels, that is the reason we also measure each ring with a digital caliper to the exact size.

Please do not use string to measure your ring size.

RING CARE

My rings are made to last a lifetime, all rings are given a clear durable multi step finish to ensure the ring remains structurally sound and beautiful. Regular hand washing is not a problem, prolonged contact with water such as swimming should not damage the ring. Solvents could and most likely will damage the ring, If you work in an environment where solvents are used or in the medical field where your hands come in contact with sanitizers we suggest you not wear your ring.

All rings require minimal care on the part of the wearer, simply use the polishing cloth we provide on a regular basis and apply a coat of Carnauba wax every 6 months. 

I have spent years working with different finishes and I believe I have found the best finish for wood inlay rings. Under normal usage the finish on my rings will last years, yes I have done all the tests the other ring makers perform, Water test, dishwasher test, dryer test, etc. But I also have gone further by placing my wood inlay rings in a rock tumbler with a variety of coins which includes pennies, dimes, nickels, quarters and half dollars. I tested the ring by running the tumbler for a couple of hours and the result showed no damage to the finish on the ring. 

I do recommend removing your ring before washing hands, swimming or showering using hand sanitizers or handling chemicals but I would recommend this no matter what type of ring you wear . 

Do not soak wood inlay rings in silver jewelry cleaner this could remove the finish and damage the ring. If you need to clean the sterling silver bands use the polishing cloth I provide you and simply wipe the silver band. The polishing cloth works great on all metals and wood.
